00:05:09.690 --> 00:05:14.350
When we talk about accessibility,
and digital accessibility,

00:05:14.350 --> 00:05:18.750
or web accessibility, we really
need to think about the basics.

00:05:18.750 --> 00:05:22.830
Many of the presenters today
have talked about WCAG,

00:05:22.830 --> 00:05:25.971
the Web Content
Accessibility Guidelines,

00:05:25.972 --> 00:05:28.140
and that's really a good set

00:05:28.140 --> 00:05:31.620
of guidelines to get started,
which is anything that has to do

00:05:31.620 --> 00:05:33.430
with digital accessibility.

00:05:33.430 --> 00:05:37.370
The principles are really sound,
and they're there to help guide us

00:05:37.370 --> 00:05:42.130
on how to create accessible
content and accessible websites.

00:05:42.130 --> 00:05:47.890
So if you are posting any kind
of learning content to WordPress,

00:05:47.890 --> 00:05:52.820
start with an accessible WordPress
theme, if that's a given.

00:05:52.820 --> 00:05:56.520
There are themes out there in
the repository that you can use.

00:05:56.520 --> 00:05:59.940
And as long as you
maintain that theme,

00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:02.580
and choose accessible
color combinations,

00:06:02.580 --> 00:06:04.710
which I'm sure people have
talked about earlier today,

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:07.790
you're starting with
a good foundation.

00:06:09.170 --> 00:06:11.840
It's also important to
organize your content.

00:06:11.840 --> 00:06:15.920
Your learning content might be
in a Learning Management System;

00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:19.610
it could be a recorded webinar,
like what we're doing today;

00:06:19.610 --> 00:06:25.510
or it could be a series of pages on
a website that have content in them.

00:06:25.510 --> 00:06:30.670
So to help all of our learners, it's
important to organize the content.

00:06:30.670 --> 00:06:32.460
Use headings where
they're appropriate.

00:06:32.460 --> 00:06:36.840
Use proper heading structure to
break up long chunks of text.

00:06:36.840 --> 00:06:41.100
It really makes things a lot
easier for our learners to digest,

00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:44.110
and it is a given.

00:06:44.110 --> 00:06:47.320
If you've got images in your
content, make sure

00:06:47.320 --> 00:06:50.370
that you include alternative
text for those images.

00:06:50.370 --> 00:06:51.810
Be descriptive.

00:06:51.810 --> 00:06:56.360
Make sure that you're explaining
what the picture is about.

00:06:56.360 --> 00:07:01.070
It doesn't need to be too wordy,
but it does need to convey the intent

00:07:01.070 --> 00:07:03.630
of the image that you're
including in your content.

00:07:04.930 --> 00:07:06.930
Of course, caption your videos.

00:07:06.930 --> 00:07:09.400
Provide audio transcripts.

00:07:09.400 --> 00:07:13.640
And don't just rely on
automated captioning.

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:17.030
They're a great place to start,
and can save you some time,

00:07:17.030 --> 00:07:21.720
but make sure that you go back
and actually edit the captions

00:07:21.720 --> 00:07:25.060
or the transcripts to make sure
they're accurate to what you've said

00:07:25.060 --> 00:07:27.720
in any of your recorded content.

00:07:27.720 --> 00:07:34.020
Even better, taking things
to an even higher level,

00:07:34.020 --> 00:07:38.560
include audio description or
described video for all the audio

00:07:38.560 --> 00:07:43.410
and video content,
or provide a described video text.

00:07:43.410 --> 00:07:47.500
I'm going to show you a bit
later in the session a couple

00:07:47.500 --> 00:07:51.860
of examples of that, but really,
what it means is describing

00:07:51.860 --> 00:07:55.910
what's happening on the screen for
somebody who can't see the screen.

00:07:55.910 --> 00:07:59.940
It could be because they're blind
and they can't see the screen,

00:07:59.940 --> 00:08:03.800
or maybe they're listening to your
content while they're cooking dinner

00:08:03.800 --> 00:08:07.270
and they don't have the
screen in front of them.

00:08:07.270 --> 00:08:10.250
It can be helpful for a lot
of different users to describe

00:08:10.250 --> 00:08:12.350
what's actually
happening on the screen.

00:08:15.900 --> 00:08:19.080
We talked about using
alternative text for images,

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:21.700
and that's an important
place to start.

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:26.630
But it's also great if you can start
incorporating inclusive imagery

00:08:26.630 --> 00:08:27.630
in your content.

00:08:29.140 --> 00:08:34.390
Inclusive imagery includes
images that portray disability,

00:08:35.690 --> 00:08:37.700
and there's different
ways of doing that.

00:08:37.700 --> 00:08:43.150
There are more and more image
libraries out there that have images

00:08:43.150 --> 00:08:48.440
that are inclusive, and it's
important to try to incorporate that

00:08:48.440 --> 00:08:49.810
into your content.

00:08:49.810 --> 00:08:53.670
It doesn't need to be
in an inspiration form.

00:08:53.670 --> 00:08:57.990
You don't want to show people
with a disability and present them

00:08:57.990 --> 00:08:58.670
as heroes.

00:08:58.670 --> 00:09:02.230
You want to present them
in normal circumstances.

00:09:02.230 --> 00:09:05.100
Like the image that I've chosen
for this particular slide,

00:09:05.100 --> 00:09:08.980
it’s a gentleman
sitting on a bench.

00:09:09.990 --> 00:09:11.590
He's got his laptop open.

00:09:11.590 --> 00:09:14.660
He's got a cup of coffee sitting
next to him on the bench.

00:09:14.660 --> 00:09:17.440
And he just happens to
have a prosthetic leg.

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:22.080
So that's a nice way to
incorporate an inclusive image

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:26.000
without turning it into a hero.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.131
The other thing to think
about is this whole concept

00:09:29.132 --> 00:09:30.430
of the Scully Effect.

00:09:31.690 --> 00:09:35.680
There was a television show back
in the day called The X-Files.

00:09:35.680 --> 00:09:40.370
And it was a show
with two FBI agents,

00:09:40.370 --> 00:09:44.010
and one of them was a female
FBI agent named Scully.

00:09:45.520 --> 00:09:51.480
She was one of the first
women to be shown on TV

00:09:51.480 --> 00:09:54.410
with a science background,
you know, quite intelligent

00:09:54.410 --> 00:09:56.090
and quite highly skilled.

00:09:57.370 --> 00:10:02.350
After that show aired, schools
were starting to notice that more

00:10:02.350 --> 00:10:07.880
and more women or young girls were
getting involved or interested

00:10:07.880 --> 00:10:11.260
in STEM Programs; science,
technology, engineering, and math.

00:10:12.560 --> 00:10:16.240
They saw her doing it and they
thought, Well, if she can do it,

00:10:16.240 --> 00:10:17.610
then I can do it.

00:10:17.610 --> 00:10:20.640
So it's now called
the Scully Effect.

00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:28.640
And it's when we see people like us,
it's easier for us to relate, right?

00:10:28.670 --> 00:10:34.530
And if we can relate, then we're
more likely to become more interested

00:10:34.530 --> 00:10:39.220
in the topic or interested in the
website or whatever the case may be.

00:10:39.220 --> 00:10:44.550
So see if you can find any
images that portray disabilities

00:10:44.550 --> 00:10:47.490
in a positive light,
and use them appropriately.

00:10:53.740 --> 00:10:54.830
Plain language.

00:10:54.830 --> 00:10:57.875
I think a couple of the
other presenters have touched

00:10:57.876 --> 00:10:58.890
on this a bit.

00:11:00.760 --> 00:11:04.190
Plain language is
important for learning,

00:11:04.190 --> 00:11:07.240
and it’s not about
dumbing down content.

00:11:07.240 --> 00:11:09.910
There's this misconception
that plain language is all

00:11:09.910 --> 00:11:20.480
about making things super simple, and
easier, or lowering the grade level.

00:11:20.480 --> 00:11:24.540
And yes, we are trying to
get to a lower-grade level

00:11:24.540 --> 00:11:28.380
with our content, but it's not
about dumbing down content.

00:11:28.380 --> 00:11:32.070
It's about making it easier for
people to digest the content,

00:11:32.070 --> 00:11:35.000
understand the content,
and absorb the content.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:37.510
It helps make learning
much more effective.

00:11:37.510 --> 00:11:40.450
It helps make learning
much more efficient.

00:11:40.450 --> 00:11:47.070
Say you're presented
with two pieces of text.

00:11:47.070 --> 00:11:49.800
One is written in plain
language, nicely organized,

00:11:49.800 --> 00:11:51.310
and might have some bullet points.

00:11:51.310 --> 00:11:53.380
And you're presented
with that same content,

00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:57.000
and it's a 15-page essay
using really big words.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:59.420
You’re probably going to
gravitate to the first one

00:11:59.420 --> 00:12:02.270
with the plain language, and the
bullet points, and the headings.

00:12:02.270 --> 00:12:04.790
It's just easier to absorb.

00:12:07.920 --> 00:12:09.250
We're all busy people.

00:12:09.250 --> 00:12:12.880
We all like to get in and get
out, learn things quickly,

00:12:12.880 --> 00:12:14.080
read things quickly.

00:12:14.080 --> 00:12:17.890
Our focus is not like it used
to be because of this world

00:12:17.890 --> 00:12:19.560
of technology that we live in.

00:12:19.560 --> 00:12:23.680
So using plain language, it can be
very effective and very helpful.

00:12:23.680 --> 00:12:28.040
There are lots of tools out there
that can help you take your content

00:12:28.040 --> 00:12:30.610
and make it a little
bit easier to read.

00:12:31.870 --> 00:12:35.860
There’s things like the Hemingway
app at Hemingwayapp.com.

00:12:38.380 --> 00:12:46.539
Microsoft Word has built-in
tools that can help you check

00:12:46.540 --> 00:12:50.640
the reading level and the statistics
in your app or your content.

00:12:52.020 --> 00:12:57.660
Artificial intelligence can be a
real help for this kind of thing.

00:12:59.160 --> 00:13:00.950
So something like a ChatGPT.

00:13:03.200 --> 00:13:11.200
As long as you are asking the
question in the right way,

00:13:11.930 --> 00:13:15.930
or using the right prompt, like,
Rephrase this original sentence

00:13:15.930 --> 00:13:17.610
using plain language.

00:13:17.610 --> 00:13:22.950
Or maybe you ask ChatGPT to Divide
this paragraph into sentences.

00:13:22.950 --> 00:13:26.070
And it might not be perfect,
but it's going to get you close.

00:13:31.940 --> 00:13:32.940
Paint a picture.

00:13:34.720 --> 00:13:37.880
So first of all, don't assume
that everyone can see your screen.

00:13:39.440 --> 00:13:42.840
Again,
it could be somebody who's blind

00:13:42.840 --> 00:13:45.580
and literally cannot see your
screen, or it could be somebody

00:13:45.580 --> 00:13:48.980
who's trying to listen
to your learning content,

00:13:48.980 --> 00:13:50.900
but they don't have the
screen in front of them.

00:13:52.030 --> 00:13:54.590
So describe the
content on the screen.

00:13:54.590 --> 00:14:02.340
Paint the picture with words so
that you can convey the intent

00:14:02.340 --> 00:14:03.810
of the content.

00:14:03.810 --> 00:14:08.390
If you're using images,
use images that support the content,

00:14:08.390 --> 00:14:11.220
not just putting them there
because they're decorative.

00:14:12.420 --> 00:14:15.800
In this particular case,
on this slide, I've chosen a picture

00:14:15.800 --> 00:14:20.010
of someone wearing a
blue button-down shirt.

00:14:20.010 --> 00:14:23.770
They've got a paintbrush in one
hand, a pen in another,

00:14:23.770 --> 00:14:26.060
and they are covered
in all sorts of paint.

00:14:26.060 --> 00:14:31.860
They're obviously very messy artist,
but they are painting a picture

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:32.980
with these tools.

00:14:34.140 --> 00:14:40.190
The other thing to do, and this
one can be difficult to undo,

00:14:40.190 --> 00:14:46.190
I have it, is using terms like as
you can see or as you can hear.

00:14:46.190 --> 00:14:49.170
Not everybody can see,
and not everybody can hear.

00:14:49.170 --> 00:14:55.480
So try to find ways that talk
about what's on your screen

00:14:55.480 --> 00:14:58.060
without using terms like that.

00:15:05.660 --> 00:15:07.510
Universal Design for Learning.

00:15:09.650 --> 00:15:13.020
As I mentioned at the
beginning, it's a big subject.

00:15:13.020 --> 00:15:14.920
There's a lot to it.

00:15:14.920 --> 00:15:21.450
It's almost like a WCAG in
that it can feel really complex

00:15:21.450 --> 00:15:24.920
and really big and hard to digest.

00:15:24.920 --> 00:15:29.240
But what I want to cover today
is just some few top-level things

00:15:29.240 --> 00:15:30.960
for you to consider.

00:15:34.060 --> 00:15:37.394
And even if you only pick one
thing and try working on that,

00:15:37.395 --> 00:15:38.600
that's great.

00:15:38.600 --> 00:15:40.850
So what is it all about?

00:15:40.850 --> 00:15:43.217
The UDL Guidelines
provide a framework

00:15:43.218 --> 00:15:47.350
to improve and optimize teaching
and learning for all people.

00:15:47.350 --> 00:15:52.890
And you can get all the information
at UDLguidelines.cast.org

00:15:52.890 --> 00:15:55.660
Cast, C-A-S-T.

00:15:56.989 --> 00:15:59.910
And it’s really three
guiding principles.

00:15:59.910 --> 00:16:02.200
You provide a multiple
means of engagement.

00:16:02.200 --> 00:16:04.350
So that supports
the why of learning.

00:16:04.350 --> 00:16:08.650
Why are we doing this? Provide
multiple means of representation.

00:16:08.650 --> 00:16:13.510
So what are we learning?
And provide multiple means of action

00:16:13.510 --> 00:16:14.330
and expression.

00:16:14.330 --> 00:16:18.080
So how are we doing the learning?
And I'm going to cover each one

00:16:18.080 --> 00:16:20.280
of these as we move forward.

00:16:22.800 --> 00:16:25.430
Provide multiple
means of engagement.

00:16:25.430 --> 00:16:27.930
Find different ways for your
learners to get involved.

00:16:27.930 --> 00:16:32.440
So that could be including
a variety of activities,

00:16:32.440 --> 00:16:34.800
like my failed attempt
at a Mentimeter.

00:16:34.800 --> 00:16:38.190
In case you were wondering why I
was doing that, that's an example

00:16:38.190 --> 00:16:43.710
of how you include activities
to get people engaged.

00:16:43.710 --> 00:16:48.000
And some people might like a
menti, some people might not.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.350
But it's there for people who
do like that sort of thing.

00:16:51.350 --> 00:16:54.670
So we try to include different
ways for people to engage

00:16:54.670 --> 00:16:59.200
with the content,
including interaction with others.

00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:02.350
So there's been a lot of that
going on today in the chat.

00:17:02.350 --> 00:17:03.460
That's great.

00:17:03.460 --> 00:17:05.750
That's a way of engaging.

00:17:05.750 --> 00:17:09.920
So if you're doing webinars,
encourage that kind of conversation.

00:17:09.920 --> 00:17:13.180
Maybe you have a Slack channel
specific to your learning,

00:17:14.360 --> 00:17:17.550
or you have a blog
post that's ongoing.

00:17:17.550 --> 00:17:20.790
There's different ways to do
it, and it all depends on

00:17:20.790 --> 00:17:23.470
what it is that you are
trying to teach people,

00:17:23.470 --> 00:17:25.850
and what best suits your
particular audience.

00:17:27.390 --> 00:17:31.140
The other thing to do is include the
same content in different formats.

00:17:32.150 --> 00:17:37.400
So when I was showing slides
with text on it, the images

00:17:37.400 --> 00:17:42.960
that I was choosing supported
the text so that somebody

00:17:42.960 --> 00:17:46.080
who's a visual learner could
look at the image and say,

00:17:46.080 --> 00:17:47.940
Oh, yes, I kind of get
what she's talking about.

00:17:47.940 --> 00:17:52.580
Kind of reinforces the content that
I'm trying to share with you today.

00:17:54.660 --> 00:18:01.910
The next slide is going to
be a very short video clip.

00:18:01.910 --> 00:18:04.350
There are captions on it.

00:18:04.350 --> 00:18:07.440
But there's also a
transcript available

00:18:07.440 --> 00:18:19.240
at
A11y.school/WPa11y/inaccessibletext.

00:18:19.240 --> 00:18:22.209
So for those of you who don't
want to watch the video,

00:18:22.210 --> 00:18:26.870
feel free to grab that
transcript and read along.

00:18:26.870 --> 00:18:27.840
OK.

00:18:33.207 --> 00:18:33.597
[automated female voice]

00:18:36.380 --> 00:18:37.990
This clip is inaccessible.

00:18:40.830 --> 00:18:43.820
So now we've got two things
on our screen right now.

00:18:43.820 --> 00:18:48.530
We have the website that
we're working on the left,

00:18:48.530 --> 00:18:52.910
and on the right
is some basic HTML.

00:18:52.910 --> 00:18:58.480
You’ll see I have my code
editor open with a document,

00:18:58.480 --> 00:19:01.890
and there's lots of
HTML in there already.

00:19:01.890 --> 00:19:05.220
But what we want to do is add
a little bit more structure

00:19:05.221 --> 00:19:06.330
to the site.

00:19:06.330 --> 00:19:10.870
So the first thing we want to
do is take a look at this menu

00:19:10.870 --> 00:19:11.870
that we've got here.

00:19:14.370 --> 00:19:18.620
There was a couple of things in
there that I touched on earlier.

00:19:18.620 --> 00:19:22.440
And even Jennison actually
talked about the whole idea

00:19:22.440 --> 00:19:23.210
of left and right.

00:19:23.210 --> 00:19:27.740
If you saw Jennison’s Keynote this
morning, it talked about that.

00:19:27.740 --> 00:19:32.170
Left and right means nothing in the
context of digital accessibility

00:19:32.170 --> 00:19:35.170
for Jennison,
for somebody who is blind.

00:19:35.170 --> 00:19:38.320
So I'm talking about something
being on the left of the screen

00:19:38.320 --> 00:19:39.780
and the right of the screen.

00:19:39.780 --> 00:19:41.640
I talked about as you can see.

00:19:41.640 --> 00:19:44.460
Well, not everybody can
see what's on the screen.

00:19:44.460 --> 00:19:50.470
So that's a snip of a
pretty typical video lesson,

00:19:50.470 --> 00:19:54.120
whether it's something that's being
shared from a high school classroom

00:19:54.120 --> 00:19:56.360
or a webinar that we've recorded.

00:19:56.360 --> 00:20:04.360
We do this all the time, and it's not
necessarily the best way to do it.

00:20:12.520 --> 00:20:18.190
The next part of UDL talks about
multiple means of representation.

00:20:18.190 --> 00:20:22.350
So find different ways for
learners to access your content,

00:20:22.350 --> 00:20:25.680
and I've been doing that by
providing a video transcript

00:20:25.680 --> 00:20:28.020
as well as showing the video.

00:20:28.020 --> 00:20:30.031
So if you want to
read the transcript,

00:20:30.032 --> 00:20:33.170
and that works better for you,
then the content is there.

00:20:33.170 --> 00:20:35.370
[Inaudible 00:20:33]

00:20:36.980 --> 00:20:38.260
the same content.

00:20:38.260 --> 00:20:42.720
If you'd rather watch the video, then
I'm presenting it to you in a video.

00:20:42.720 --> 00:20:46.760
Multiple means of representation is
really about finding different ways

00:20:46.760 --> 00:20:50.620
to give your learners
content, obviously making sure

00:20:50.620 --> 00:20:53.167
that your content is
accessible in whatever way

00:20:53.168 --> 00:20:54.600
that you are providing it.

00:20:54.600 --> 00:20:56.930
But provide it in different ways.

00:20:56.930 --> 00:20:58.210
We all learn differently.

00:20:58.210 --> 00:21:01.900
We all have a preferred
way of doing things.

00:21:03.020 --> 00:21:06.460
So give that opportunity
to your students as well.

00:21:07.690 --> 00:21:11.680
Also look for different ways to
check your learner's understanding.

00:21:11.680 --> 00:21:18.390
It could be a quick conversation
in a classroom setting.

00:21:18.390 --> 00:21:21.890
It could be a quick
chat in a Zoom Webinar.

00:21:21.890 --> 00:21:23.950
Again, it could be a chat
in something like Slack.

00:21:25.070 --> 00:21:30.650
So think about how you can use
different ways to deliver information

00:21:30.650 --> 00:21:32.330
and also to check understanding.

00:21:33.880 --> 00:21:35.250
I'm going to show another clip.

00:21:36.890 --> 00:21:46.423
Again, the transcript is available
at A11y.school/WPa11y/accessibletext.

00:21:50.260 --> 00:21:50.809
[Automated female voice]

00:21:50.810 --> 00:21:52.580
This clip is accessible.

00:21:55.460 --> 00:21:55.780
Great.

00:21:55.780 --> 00:22:00.220
So now that we've switched
screens, we have our website

00:22:00.220 --> 00:22:02.990
on the left side of the screen.

00:22:02.990 --> 00:22:05.090
And this website,
it's pretty basic.

00:22:05.090 --> 00:22:09.990
We have some menu with home,
about, history, contact.

00:22:09.990 --> 00:22:12.740
A heading that says
Welcome to our website.

00:22:12.740 --> 00:22:18.090
Some text with a
link out to WCAG 2.1.

00:22:18.090 --> 00:22:21.480
And a cat that's taken
an accidental selfie.

00:22:21.480 --> 00:22:27.960
This little white cat is staring up
at the phone with great, big eyes.

00:22:27.960 --> 00:22:31.980
Clearly, it found the selfie button
and seems to be pretty confused

00:22:31.980 --> 00:22:33.590
by what he's done.

00:22:33.590 --> 00:22:35.390
Cute all in all.

00:22:35.390 --> 00:22:40.760
On the right side of the screen,
we have the HTML that is used

00:22:40.760 --> 00:22:43.080
to create the website.

00:22:43.080 --> 00:22:49.260
So at the top of the screen,
the HTML is pretty standard.

00:22:49.260 --> 00:22:54.700
We have the doctype that says,
angle bracket, exclamation,

00:22:54.700 --> 00:22:58.020
doctype HTML, close angle bracket.

00:22:58.020 --> 00:23:01.730
And that tells the browser
that this is an HTML document,

00:23:01.730 --> 00:23:08.260
and it needs to think
about it that way.

00:23:08.260 --> 00:23:11.100
So it's better than the first one.

00:23:11.100 --> 00:23:14.960
I've been much more
descriptive in this video.

00:23:14.960 --> 00:23:18.610
I described the cat with
the accidental selfie.

00:23:18.610 --> 00:23:20.670
I didn't even touch on
that in the first video.

00:23:21.940 --> 00:23:29.940
I started talking about all the HTML
code that's in the HTML document.

00:23:31.810 --> 00:23:35.330
And really, when you're doing
something, especially something

00:23:35.330 --> 00:23:38.250
that's technically related, you’re
going to have to find a balance

00:23:38.250 --> 00:23:42.930
between saying every single
character that's on the screen

00:23:42.930 --> 00:23:46.720
and maybe finding shortcuts,
like saying that Remember to open

00:23:46.720 --> 00:23:50.710
and close your tags, rather
than saying Open angle bracket,

00:23:50.710 --> 00:23:54.400
close angle bracket
for every line of HTML.

00:23:54.400 --> 00:23:59.450
So that's something that you will
need to kind of adapt to your kind

00:23:59.450 --> 00:24:00.450
of content.

00:24:01.260 --> 00:24:06.010
Although, keep in mind
that not everybody's going

00:24:06.010 --> 00:24:08.950
to be watching you
type on the screen.

00:24:08.950 --> 00:24:12.270
So if you're typing
something, say it out loud.

00:24:12.270 --> 00:24:15.030
So that's what integrated
described video is all about.

00:24:15.030 --> 00:24:18.730
It's describing what's
happening on the screen.

00:24:18.730 --> 00:24:22.270
It's almost like listening
to a baseball game.

00:24:22.270 --> 00:24:25.740
My husband and I are big
Toronto Blue Jays fans.

00:24:25.740 --> 00:24:28.890
We listen quite often on the
radio, and radio announcers

00:24:28.890 --> 00:24:32.380
for baseball are really good at
describing not just what's happening

00:24:32.380 --> 00:24:36.100
on the playing field, but what's
happening around the players

00:24:36.100 --> 00:24:37.310
and in the stadium itself.

00:24:37.310 --> 00:24:40.480
So think of yourself as a
baseball announcer on the radio,

00:24:40.480 --> 00:24:43.570
and that can give you some
clues or hints as to how to kind

00:24:43.570 --> 00:24:47.520
of move forward with things.

00:24:49.310 --> 00:24:57.260
The last principle
of Universal Design

00:24:57.260 --> 00:25:00.310
for Learning is providing multiple
means of action and expression.

00:25:01.730 --> 00:25:05.040
So give learners options for
demonstrating their understanding

00:25:05.040 --> 00:25:06.850
of the content.

00:25:06.850 --> 00:25:11.690
That could be giving them a
choice of assignment options.

00:25:12.800 --> 00:25:15.670
Maybe you've always asked for
people to submit an essay.

00:25:15.670 --> 00:25:18.680
Well, maybe open it up to them.

00:25:18.680 --> 00:25:21.040
Maybe let them choose
how they want to deliver.

00:25:21.040 --> 00:25:24.053
It could be a
PowerPoint presentation,

00:25:24.054 --> 00:25:26.370
or it could be a short video.

00:25:26.370 --> 00:25:29.760
Let them choose how they want
to explain things to you.

00:25:31.300 --> 00:25:37.640
If you're using Quizizz,
which is quite common,

00:25:37.640 --> 00:25:44.810
especially in online learning,
use different types of questions.

00:25:44.810 --> 00:25:48.060
So true or false, multiple
choice, fill in the blank.

00:25:48.060 --> 00:25:53.040
Don't just make it a whole 25-set
question of true and false.

00:25:53.040 --> 00:25:54.620
That's not helpful for people.

00:25:54.620 --> 00:25:57.980
Give them different types
of questions to answer.

00:26:01.970 --> 00:26:04.300
We’re going to put
this to the test.

00:26:04.300 --> 00:26:06.890
What's your favorite
kind of quiz question?

00:26:06.890 --> 00:26:11.440
I want you to use the Zoom reactions
to tell me what you actually like.

00:26:11.440 --> 00:26:16.660
If you prefer true or false,
use the clapping-hands reaction.

00:26:16.660 --> 00:26:19.850
If you like multiple
choice, use the thumbs up.

00:26:20.950 --> 00:26:24.120
And if you like fill in the
blank, use a heart.

00:26:28.600 --> 00:26:31.170
I'm starting to see
reactions floating up.

00:26:32.790 --> 00:26:38.420
And multiple choice seems to
be the winner, by a long shot.

00:26:38.420 --> 00:26:40.670
That’s really interesting.

00:26:40.670 --> 00:26:42.650
And I’m curious,
I wonder why that is.

00:26:44.220 --> 00:26:45.080
Thank you for that.

00:26:45.080 --> 00:26:51.740
Fill in the blank is not
very popular, I don't think.

00:26:51.740 --> 00:26:57.920
OK, so we're getting near the end.

00:26:57.920 --> 00:26:59.410
So how did I use this?

00:26:59.410 --> 00:27:03.040
I talked about UDL, but how
did I actually use it myself?

00:27:03.040 --> 00:27:05.060
So providing multiple
means of engagement.

00:27:05.060 --> 00:27:08.140
We had the opening poll with
Mentimeter, which failed,

00:27:08.140 --> 00:27:09.670
but it was an attempt.

00:27:11.230 --> 00:27:15.190
We used reactions just
now to get you engaged.

00:27:15.190 --> 00:27:17.770
How did I use multiple
means of representation?

00:27:19.060 --> 00:27:23.750
I had images that match the content,
and I provided video transcripts

00:27:23.750 --> 00:27:25.110
for the videos that I showed.

00:27:27.210 --> 00:27:32.100
How did I provide multiple
means of action and expression?

00:27:32.100 --> 00:27:33.430
I use different types of media.

00:27:33.430 --> 00:27:36.570
Some of them were images,
some of them were video.

00:27:37.770 --> 00:27:40.360
Use this concept of scaffolding.

00:27:40.360 --> 00:27:44.600
Scaffolding is like building
one lesson on top of another.

00:27:45.660 --> 00:27:49.820
So I told you what we're going to
talk about; we talked about it.

00:27:49.820 --> 00:27:55.670
And I provided you with different
ways of seeing what that looked like

00:27:55.670 --> 00:27:57.520
or what that was like in practice.

00:28:03.080 --> 00:28:06.260
This has been mentioned before:
progress over perfection.

00:28:07.630 --> 00:28:08.720
I'm not perfect.

00:28:08.720 --> 00:28:10.750
I don't get everything right.

00:28:10.750 --> 00:28:14.710
I’ve heard myself giving this
presentation and using words

00:28:14.710 --> 00:28:18.640
that I probably wished I hadn't
used, or describe things in ways

00:28:18.640 --> 00:28:21.710
that I hadn’t,
but I made an effort.

00:28:21.710 --> 00:28:24.310
I tried to do as best I could.

00:28:24.310 --> 00:28:27.960
I tried to incorporate as many
things as I possibly could

00:28:27.960 --> 00:28:30.859
to make this a more engaging and,

00:28:30.860 --> 00:28:34.460
hopefully,
educational session for you.

00:28:34.460 --> 00:28:37.750
So my question back to you
is, what can you do

00:28:37.750 --> 00:28:39.590
to make your lessons
more accessible?

