you're getting closer.

00:32:48.980 --> 00:32:52.050
But having developed a
couple of learning programs

00:32:52.050 --> 00:32:56.310
using something like a
WordPress plugin, an LMS plugin,

00:32:57.570 --> 00:32:59.860
they’re not great out of the box.

00:32:59.860 --> 00:33:02.180
They're not great in the
back-end for anybody who's got

00:33:02.180 --> 00:33:05.510
to manage the content
and get it in there.

00:33:05.510 --> 00:33:11.180
They're also not great for somebody
who's using assistive technology

00:33:11.180 --> 00:33:12.930
and going through the process.

00:33:14.450 --> 00:33:18.290
We had many users testing,
and we had to, at the end

00:33:18.290 --> 00:33:23.470
of the day,
really simplify what was out there

00:33:23.470 --> 00:33:25.050
in order to make
it work for people.

00:33:25.050 --> 00:33:29.720
So out of the box,
probably not going to be accessible.

00:33:29.720 --> 00:33:31.290
You're probably still going
to need to do some work,

00:33:31.290 --> 00:33:33.490
and you're certainly going to
need to get end users involved

00:33:33.490 --> 00:33:35.050
to see what works and
what doesn't work.

00:33:37.170 --> 00:33:37.610
>> BEN: Yes.

00:33:37.610 --> 00:33:41.490
And I know that VPATs
are a useful tool,

00:33:41.490 --> 00:33:45.880
or Accessibility Conformance Reports
are a useful tool in that search,

00:33:45.880 --> 00:33:47.145
but you always have to
[Inaudible 00:33:47].

00:33:48.540 --> 00:33:50.240
>> SANDI: Test, test, test.

00:33:50.240 --> 00:33:51.260
[chuckles]

00:33:52.820 --> 00:33:56.640
>> BEN: Someone anonymous asked:
Do you have any recommendations

00:33:56.640 --> 00:33:59.850
or resources on how to
effectively describe images?

00:34:00.780 --> 00:34:01.900
>> SANDI: Resources.

00:34:01.900 --> 00:34:07.920
I think that's more of a skill
that you have to develop.

00:34:07.920 --> 00:34:14.070
So it's something that I think is
a bit of an art form personally.

00:34:23.460 --> 00:34:26.660
Somebody once described
it to me as this:

00:34:27.940 --> 00:34:30.900
Try to describe it like you were
describing an image over the phone

00:34:30.900 --> 00:34:32.350
to your friend.

00:34:32.350 --> 00:34:35.760
So if you can describe it
in a couple of sentences,

00:34:35.760 --> 00:34:37.580
then you're probably good.

00:34:37.580 --> 00:34:43.420
I'm not familiar with specific
resources that talk about

00:34:43.420 --> 00:34:47.270
how to write accessible
text or alternative text,

00:34:49.450 --> 00:34:52.090
but I do know that keeping it
simple, keeping it short,

00:34:52.090 --> 00:34:55.370
keeping it descriptive is
really what you're going for,

00:34:55.370 --> 00:34:56.540
as well as the purpose of it.

00:34:56.540 --> 00:35:00.080
If you're trying to describe an
image that's just kind of fluff,

00:35:00.080 --> 00:35:03.120
it's there to fill
in a space on a page,

00:35:03.120 --> 00:35:04.500
then maybe you don't even
need the image at all.

00:35:05.570 --> 00:35:06.800
Same thing with PowerPoints.

00:35:06.800 --> 00:35:08.910
Do you really need an
image on every slide?

00:35:08.910 --> 00:35:12.570
If that slide doesn't need an image,
don't stick something in there

00:35:12.570 --> 00:35:15.990
just for the sake of
sticking something in there.

00:35:15.990 --> 00:35:17.440
It needs to add value.

00:35:17.440 --> 00:35:21.930
Sometimes I think even
that curation of content

00:35:21.930 --> 00:35:23.880
can make a big
difference down the road.

00:35:25.086 --> 00:35:26.146
>> BEN: Yes.

00:35:27.280 --> 00:35:32.870
Somebody said in a talk earlier:
Describe it like you're describing it

00:35:32.870 --> 00:35:34.910
to your grandmother over the phone.

00:35:34.910 --> 00:35:37.800
That kind of infused the care
and attention to the outcome,

00:35:37.800 --> 00:35:40.110
like empathy and
care for the outcome,

00:35:40.110 --> 00:35:41.590
which I really like
thinking about it that way.

00:35:42.260 --> 00:35:42.950
>> SANDI: Yes, that’s good.

00:35:42.950 --> 00:35:43.250
Yes.

00:35:43.250 --> 00:35:47.800
>> BEN: I'll also quickly plug a
talk that's coming up later today

00:35:47.800 --> 00:35:52.470
by Caroline Desrosiers: Alt
Text in the Age of Automation:

00:35:52.470 --> 00:35:53.689
How's it Actually Going?

00:35:53.690 --> 00:35:56.230
I think folks will get
some interesting insights

00:35:56.230 --> 00:35:59.240
on describing alt text and
tools that do that well

00:35:59.240 --> 00:36:00.840
or not from there.

00:36:00.840 --> 00:36:05.990
Question from Jennifer:
Hello from Koolway Sports.

00:36:05.990 --> 00:36:09.620
Should every social-media post have
a description in English and French?

00:36:11.280 --> 00:36:13.820
>> SANDI: Oh, she's a fellow
Canadian, I'm guessing.

00:36:13.820 --> 00:36:17.730
I'm going to say that's going
to depend on your audience.

00:36:17.730 --> 00:36:22.510
If you are speaking to
a bilingual audience,

00:36:22.510 --> 00:36:26.330
or you're a national organization
and you're speaking to people

00:36:26.330 --> 00:36:30.030
on social media in both
English and French, then yes,

00:36:30.030 --> 00:36:32.500
I think you need to have
it in both languages.

00:36:32.500 --> 00:36:36.630
If your audience is predominantly
English or predominantly French,

00:36:38.620 --> 00:36:41.980
then you're probably fine to
just write your alternative text

00:36:41.980 --> 00:36:46.030
or your descriptions in the
language that your audience uses.

00:36:46.030 --> 00:36:50.990
We come from in a marketing
background, our company.

00:36:50.990 --> 00:36:52.160
It's knowing your audience.

00:36:52.160 --> 00:36:53.240
Who are you talking to?

00:36:53.240 --> 00:36:56.200
If you don't know who your audience
is, it becomes very difficult

00:36:56.200 --> 00:36:58.490
to give them the
content that they need.

00:36:58.490 --> 00:37:01.580
If you know your audience is
English and French-speaking,

00:37:01.580 --> 00:37:02.950
then give them both.

00:37:05.180 --> 00:37:05.770
>> BEN: Great.

00:37:05.770 --> 00:37:06.770
Thanks.

00:37:08.270 --> 00:37:14.650
Question from Karine [phonetic]:

00:37:16.660 --> 00:37:19.400
What about saying above or below?

00:37:19.400 --> 00:37:21.660
That’s probably wrong too.

00:37:21.660 --> 00:37:22.480
>> SANDI: Oh.

00:37:22.480 --> 00:37:24.930
Yes, it's not ideal.

00:37:24.930 --> 00:37:32.860
When trying to describe
things on a screen, you need

00:37:32.860 --> 00:37:38.180
to provide context for people
who can't see the screen, right?

00:37:38.180 --> 00:37:40.050
Left and right, top and bottom.

00:37:41.220 --> 00:37:45.020
Top and bottom is probably better
because content is read top

00:37:45.020 --> 00:37:46.020
to bottom.

00:37:46.830 --> 00:37:47.850
It's very linear.

00:37:47.850 --> 00:37:50.380
So if you think about
your content being linear,

00:37:51.730 --> 00:37:54.300
I don't think you're
getting into trouble.

00:37:54.300 --> 00:37:57.550
I think where people get into trouble
when they say things like left

00:37:57.550 --> 00:38:00.790
and right or top and bottom
is that they don't provide

00:38:00.790 --> 00:38:03.640
any additional context around it.

00:38:03.640 --> 00:38:07.620
So you could say, On one side
of my screen, I have the picture

00:38:07.620 --> 00:38:10.420
of the cat taking a selfie,
and on the other side

00:38:10.420 --> 00:38:15.950
of the screen, I have my
text editor showing the code.

00:38:15.950 --> 00:38:18.700
It doesn't matter really if
it's on the left or the right

00:38:18.700 --> 00:38:20.920
in the grand scheme of things.

00:38:20.920 --> 00:38:24.500
So it could be just as
simple as doing that.

00:38:24.500 --> 00:38:27.690
It could be, you know, instead
of saying, the top or the bottom

00:38:27.690 --> 00:38:31.260
of the screen, you could say,
At the beginning of my code,

00:38:31.260 --> 00:38:35.190
there's this, and you know,
20 lines later, there's this.

00:38:36.500 --> 00:38:41.080
So it's subtle, and it's not
something you have to do overnight.

00:38:41.080 --> 00:38:44.790
It's just like trying to listen
to yourself when talking.

00:38:44.790 --> 00:38:46.688
And when you start
listening to yourself

00:38:46.689 --> 00:38:48.170
and hearing what you're saying,

00:38:48.170 --> 00:38:50.210
you catch yourself
more often [chuckles]

00:38:50.210 --> 00:38:52.740
than you realize and
go, Ah, it wasn't great.

00:38:52.740 --> 00:38:54.180
I need to redo that next time. Yes.

00:38:54.180 --> 00:38:54.660
>> BEN: Yes.

00:38:55.460 --> 00:38:57.800
>> SANDI: As long as you're
aware and paying attention.

00:38:59.360 --> 00:39:02.040
That's always step number one.

00:39:03.084 --> 00:39:03.652
>> BEN: Yes.

00:39:04.780 --> 00:39:10.540
Question from Sam: When building
a course with an LMS in WordPress,

00:39:10.540 --> 00:39:15.930
should I stay away from using an
accordion to hide or show lessons

00:39:15.930 --> 00:39:16.950
and transcripts?

00:39:19.020 --> 00:39:22.020
>> SANDI: If the accordion is
built in an accessible fashion,

00:39:22.020 --> 00:39:25.480
I don't think there's any
issue with using an accordion.

00:39:25.480 --> 00:39:29.520
You get into trouble when
you're using plugins and widgets

00:39:29.520 --> 00:39:33.360
and blocks that had been built for
WordPress, but haven't been built

00:39:33.360 --> 00:39:35.410
with accessibility in mind.

00:39:35.410 --> 00:39:37.170
That's where you get into trouble.

00:39:37.170 --> 00:39:40.380
I would say that if you are
going to use an accordion,

00:39:40.380 --> 00:39:47.340
make sure that the question
or the topic or whatever it is

00:39:49.210 --> 00:39:56.440
that's visible when it's not
exposed, make sure it's clear.

00:39:56.440 --> 00:39:58.380
An FAQ is an easy
way to describe it.

00:39:58.380 --> 00:40:02.910
So if you have an FAQ page,
make sure the questions are

00:40:02.910 --> 00:40:05.550
what are visible before the
box [Inaudible 00:40:05].

00:40:05.550 --> 00:40:06.680
Make sure those are clear.

00:40:08.450 --> 00:40:12.380
If you can make them so that
they are headings, that's great.

00:40:12.380 --> 00:40:14.258
If you make the FAQ
questions headings,

00:40:14.259 --> 00:40:15.620
then it's great for somebody

00:40:15.620 --> 00:40:18.890
who might use a screen reader to
just navigate through the list

00:40:18.890 --> 00:40:19.750
of headings.

00:40:19.750 --> 00:40:22.460
So there's nothing wrong with
them if they're done properly.

00:40:23.533 --> 00:40:24.041
>> BEN: Great.

00:40:27.310 --> 00:40:30.740
Question from Joshua:
I've seen some websites

00:40:30.740 --> 00:40:33.390
where they include
‘accessibility options,’

00:40:34.990 --> 00:40:37.740
where users can choose the
look and feel of the web pages

00:40:37.740 --> 00:40:39.710
on the site to better
suit their needs.

00:40:39.710 --> 00:40:42.100
Is that better, do you think,
than trying to make your website

00:40:42.100 --> 00:40:46.440
as inclusive as possible, where you
can’t cover all disabilities at once?

00:40:46.440 --> 00:40:48.070
>> SANDI: Yes.

00:40:48.070 --> 00:40:51.850
I think that's a personal
preference, I would say.

00:40:53.130 --> 00:40:57.060
I'm all for doing it
right from the get go.

00:40:57.060 --> 00:41:00.600
And it marries in nicely with the
whole idea of Universal Design

00:41:00.600 --> 00:41:01.500
for Learning.

00:41:01.500 --> 00:41:04.410
Universal design for Learning is
intended to make learning good

00:41:04.410 --> 00:41:05.940
for everybody.

00:41:05.940 --> 00:41:10.310
Like I said in the presentation,
we all learn differently.

00:41:10.310 --> 00:41:12.710
We all need different
ways to learn.

00:41:12.710 --> 00:41:16.940
So if you're building an
accessible WordPress theme

00:41:16.940 --> 00:41:21.200
with accessible content that's
well structured, well organized,

00:41:21.200 --> 00:41:25.530
your theme colors are
appropriate, you don't have bells

00:41:25.530 --> 00:41:27.890
and whistles happening
all over the place.

00:41:27.890 --> 00:41:32.250
I'm not so sure that those
accessibility options are going

00:41:32.250 --> 00:41:36.430
to make that much more of a
difference for the end users.

00:41:36.430 --> 00:41:39.810
And some people could argue that
having all those extra options

00:41:39.810 --> 00:41:44.390
can become clutter,
and can be too much information

00:41:44.390 --> 00:41:46.830
for some people,
and can become a distraction.

00:41:46.830 --> 00:41:49.710
So it's a balance, right?

00:41:51.500 --> 00:41:56.510
I think if you can build
out a site with content,

00:41:56.510 --> 00:42:00.450
whether it's learning content
or a regular website that works

00:42:00.450 --> 00:42:04.440
without making those accessibility
options available, that's great.

00:42:04.440 --> 00:42:08.140
Also use your accessibility
statement to talk about things

00:42:08.140 --> 00:42:12.270
that maybe are not perfect or
that you're still working on.

00:42:12.270 --> 00:42:15.640
And always be available to provide
additional support to a user

00:42:15.640 --> 00:42:16.910
that needs it.

00:42:16.910 --> 00:42:20.960
Maybe you've done everything
you could possibly think of

00:42:20.960 --> 00:42:26.240
to deliver an accessible learning
program, you’ve used all the concepts

00:42:26.240 --> 00:42:29.250
of UDL, and still it
doesn't work for somebody.

00:42:29.250 --> 00:42:30.880
You're going to be
dealing with that.

00:42:30.880 --> 00:42:33.640
It's almost impossible
to avoid that.

00:42:33.640 --> 00:42:37.560
So I think it comes down
to personal preference

00:42:37.560 --> 00:42:38.840
and what your audience needs.

00:42:38.840 --> 00:42:43.540
If you've got people coming to you
time after time after time saying,

00:42:43.540 --> 00:42:46.200
I want those accessibility
options, then put them on.

00:42:46.200 --> 00:42:47.050
[chuckles]

00:42:47.050 --> 00:42:51.460
But if they're not being used,
then maybe you can get rid of them.

00:42:53.020 --> 00:42:55.600
>> BEN: And I think it also
depends on how those options are

00:42:55.600 --> 00:42:58.820
being injected, like,
if they're being, like, JavaScript,

00:42:58.820 --> 00:43:01.060
or if they're actually built
into the semantics of the site.

00:43:02.530 --> 00:43:03.670
Again, progress over perfection.

00:43:03.670 --> 00:43:06.030
But some solutions that
do that sort of thing

00:43:06.030 --> 00:43:08.000
are actually a step
backwards, and make it worse.

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:12.460
So I would say always make sure
you're testing with real users

00:43:12.460 --> 00:43:15.130
to see if those options are making
it better for them or worse.

00:43:15.130 --> 00:43:16.170
>> SANDI: Exactly.

00:43:16.583 --> 00:43:16.863
Yes.

00:43:19.020 --> 00:43:22.540
>> BEN: Anonymous question: Do
you ever post a presentation

00:43:22.540 --> 00:43:26.070
after the lesson to a website?

00:43:26.070 --> 00:43:29.120
And then how do you make it
accessible? I'm not sure...

00:43:29.120 --> 00:43:33.590
Do you ever post a presentation
after the lesson to a website?

00:43:33.590 --> 00:43:35.550
And then how do you
make it accessible?

00:43:36.300 --> 00:43:37.260
>> SANDI: Ah, OK.

00:43:37.260 --> 00:43:40.290
So I think this is the question.

00:43:40.290 --> 00:43:44.690
When I first started to teach
at Mohawk, it was pre-pandemic

00:43:44.690 --> 00:43:46.320
so we were in class.

00:43:46.320 --> 00:43:48.680
And, of course,
we moved to online learning.

00:43:48.680 --> 00:43:51.500
The lectures were being
recorded via Zoom.

00:43:51.500 --> 00:43:53.640
We would have Zoom classes.

00:43:53.640 --> 00:43:56.410
And then after the fact,
they would be captioned.

00:43:56.410 --> 00:43:59.990
And when they were captioned,
they would go up on the platform,

00:43:59.990 --> 00:44:02.220
which I can't remember
what it was at the time.

00:44:02.220 --> 00:44:04.300
So yes, they were made available.

00:44:04.300 --> 00:44:07.810
Also, there were students who would
ask, Is it up yet? Is it up yet?

00:44:07.810 --> 00:44:10.700
Because they want to go back
and they want to review it.

00:44:10.700 --> 00:44:12.530
They may be taking notes.

00:44:12.530 --> 00:44:13.620
They may have missed the class.

00:44:13.620 --> 00:44:15.940
They may have to go let
the dog out in the middle

00:44:15.940 --> 00:44:18.610
of the important
part of the lecture.

00:44:18.610 --> 00:44:23.960
So yes, that was very much a
habit of what we did, for sure.

00:44:23.960 --> 00:44:25.430
I think even for
something like this too.

00:44:25.430 --> 00:44:29.690
I know you guys are recording;
you're going to have it captioned,

00:44:29.690 --> 00:44:31.760
and then have it available
for the attendees.

00:44:31.760 --> 00:44:35.590
And that's great, because it's
hard to focus for 24 hours,

00:44:35.590 --> 00:44:38.300
first of all,
and retain all that information.

00:44:38.300 --> 00:44:43.870
Plus, there's some presentations
that would be great to watch again.

00:44:43.870 --> 00:44:44.700
So why not?

00:44:44.700 --> 00:44:45.700
Why wouldn't you?

00:44:46.920 --> 00:44:47.800
Hi, Christina.

00:44:47.800 --> 00:44:48.750
[laughs]

00:44:48.750 --> 00:44:49.280
Sorry.

00:44:49.280 --> 00:44:50.680
Attendee.

00:44:50.680 --> 00:44:51.870
[laughs]

00:44:51.870 --> 00:44:54.890
>> BEN: All good.

